Introduction.

The data set includes records and observations from the year 2012 to 2018 for traffic violations that occurred in Maryland. The total number of records in the data set is 1.04 million, with 431,200 remaining after sample distribution. There are 35 columns in which the observations are organized.

“A traffic violation is defined as an act that violates the traffic laws of the state or country in question.”(Admin, 2020)

General Examples of Traffic Violation
  • Over speed
  • Not using the seat belt
  • Avoiding stop signs and red light
  • Driving under drugs/alcohol influence and so on.
Understanding some important columns in the Data set.
  • Agency : Agency issuing the traffic violation. (Example: MCP is Montgomery County Police)
  • Alcohol : If the traffic violation included an alcohol related
  • Belts : If traffic violation involved a seat belt violation.
  • Contributed To Accident : If the traffic violation was a contributing factor in an accident.
  • Date Of Stop : Date of the traffic violation.
  • Fatal : If traffic violation involved a fatality.
  • Gender : Gender of the driver (F = Female, M = Male)
  • HAZMAT : If the traffic violation involved hazardous materials.
  • Latitude : Latitude location of the traffic violation.
  • Longitude : Longitude location of the traffic violation.
  • Personal Injury : If traffic violation involved Personal Injury.
  • Property Damage : If traffic violation involved Property Damage.
  • Race : Race of the driver. (Example: Asian, Black, White, Other, etc.)
  • SubAgency : Court code representing the district of assignment of the officer. R15 = 1st district, Rockville B15 = 2nd district, Bethesda SS15 = 3rd district, Silver Spring WG15 = 4th district, Wheaton G15 = 5th district, Germantown M15 = 6th district, Gaithersburg / Montgomery Village HQ15 = Headquarters and Special Operations *Time Of Stop : Time of the traffic violation.
  • VehicleType : Type of vehicle (Examples: Automobile, Station Wagon, Heavy Duty Truck, etc.)
  • Violation Type : Violation type. (Examples: Warning, Citation, SERO)
  • Work Zone : If the traffic violation was in a work zone.

Data encoding for Heatmap

df_Daksh <- df_Daksh %>%
  mutate(belten = if_else(Belts == "No", 0, 1)) %>%
  mutate(alcoholn = if_else(Alcohol == "No", 0, 1))%>%
  mutate(hazmatn = if_else(HAZMAT == "No", 0,1))%>%
  mutate(personinjuryn = if_else(Personal.Injury == "No", 0, 1))%>%
  mutate(propdamn = if_else(Property.Damage == "No", 0, 1))%>%
  mutate(fataln = if_else(Fatal == "No", 0, 1))%>%
  mutate(workzonen = if_else(Work.Zone == "No", 0, 1))%>%
  mutate(genn = if_else(Gender == "F", 0, 1)) %>%
  mutate(violation_y = if_else(Belts == "Yes" | Commercial.License == "Yes"
                               | Alcohol == "Yes" | HAZMAT == "Yes", "Yes", "No"))

df_Daksh <- df_Daksh %>%
  mutate(Day_view = case_when(hour <=5 ~ "Midnight",
                              (hour >5 & hour <=11) ~ "Morning",
                              (hour>11 & hour <=16)  ~ "Afternoon",
                              (hour > 16 & hour <= 20) ~ "Evening",
                               hour >20 ~ "Night"))
df_Daksh <- df_Daksh %>%
  mutate(Dayn = case_when(Day_view == "Midnight" ~ 0,
                          Day_view == "Morning" ~ 1,
                          Day_view == "Afternoon" ~ 2,
                          Day_view == "Evening" ~ 3,
                          Day_view == "Night" ~ 4))

Chi-square test of independce

  • We will check if the relation of various categorical columns with othe categorical columns

  • H0 = The variable Gender and Violation Type are Independent.

  • H1 = The variable Gender and Violation Type are Dependent.

chi1 <- xtabs(~ Gender + Violation.Type, data = df_Daksh)
chi1
##       Violation.Type
## Gender Citation  ESERO   SERO Warning
##      F    59512   6605     80   75979
##      M   142516  14727    231  131060
##      U       67      2      0     421
chisq.test(chi1)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  chi1
## X-squared = 2756.1, df = 6, p-value < 2.2e-16

  • From the above observation we understand that the Gender and Violation type have some dependence.

  • H0 = The variable Race and Violation Type are Independent.

  • H1 = The variable Race and Violation Type are Dependent.

chi2 <- xtabs(~ Race + Violation.Type, data = df_Daksh)
